Rating: 3
I happened to serve a salad with a simple balsamic dressing (basically just a very thick balsamic vinegar with a little dijon mustard, to complement the dijon in the recipe, and some sweetening and salt and pepper) on the same plate as the chicken. We decided that the chicken tasted good dipped in the balsamic, so another option for this recipe might be a simple balsamic sauce to go with it, or to just deliberately serve it with such a salad to save a sauce-making step. Like others, I may cut back on the tarragon next time, as it intensified during cooking. Also, I did mine with plain, boneless skinless chicken breasts, and they were nice. No sense caking this nice topping on top of skin. A healthier option still would be to substitute bran or other things for some or all of the breadcrumbs next time. I found that ANY added salt was a mistake, as the horseradish carried such a salty effect into the coating, so I will eliminate that next time.

